[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Walter Maurice Ellerton''' [[Order of the Bath|CB]] (5 August 1870 - 27 November 1948) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who went on to be [[East Indies Station|Commander-in-Chief, East Indies Station]].

==Naval career==
Ellerton joined the [[Royal Navy]] in 1884.<ref name=admirals>[http://www.admirals.org.uk/admirals/individual.php?RecNo=362 Royal Navy Flag Officers 1904-1945]</ref> He served in [[World War I]] and, as [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] of [[HMS Cornwall (1902)|HMS ''Cornwall'']], took part in the [[Battle of the Falkland Islands]] in December 1914.<ref>[http://www.naval-history.net/WW1Battle1412Falklands.htm World War I Naval Battles]</ref> He was commended for his service in [[Gallipoli]] in 1915.<ref>[http://freespace.virgin.net/bob.ellerton/London_Gazette_1900.htm London Gazette]</ref>

Promoted to [[Rear Admiral]] in 1921,<ref name=admirals/> he was appointed Director of Training and Staff Duties at the [[Admiralty]] that year,<ref>Whitaker's Almanack 1922</ref> Senior Naval Officer in [[Gibraltar]] in 1923<ref>Whitaker's Almanack 1924</ref> and [[East Indies Station|Commander-in-Chief, East Indies Station]] in 1925.<ref>Whitaker's Almanack 1926</ref> He retired in 1929.<ref>Whitaker's Almanack 1930</ref>

==Family== 
In 1909 he married Gwendolen Mary Kennard.<ref>[http://thepeerage.com/p23732.htm The Peerage.com]</ref>

